et I felt myself rising to the occasion. Ah, what a wonder is the male sex organ. It does more of my thinking for me than I do.<br>
<br>
A glance at the wind-up clock next to Eva's bed made the decision for me. I was an hour late.<br>
<br>
&quot;Gotta go.&quot; I apologized, springing out of bed. I pulled on my pants as Eva pouted.<br>
<br>
&quot;Come on, Lennon.&quot; she purred when she saw she wasn't going to guilt me back to her more than ample bosum. &quot;Don't you want to stay?&quot;<br>
<br>
Yes, yes, I thought. &quot;Nope. Can't do it.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What, have to get back to the wife or something?&quot; she teased.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, actually, yes.&quot; I replied rather sheepishly.<br>
<br>
The ashtray hit me between the eyes before I could register she threw it. It drew blood. My head reeled. Damn, what an arm she had!<br>
<br>
&quot;You son-of-a-bitch!&quot; she screamed. &quot;When did you get married?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Um, last week.&quot; I managed, trying to button up my shirt without passing out.<br>
<br>
&quot;Last week?!&quot; She was livid. The lamp followed the ashtray. Fortunately I was bending over to pull on my shoes, and it sailed over my head to shatter against the wall. More fortunately, it wasn't lit, or the room would light up like a torch from the spilled oil.<br>
<br>
&quot;Who is she?&quot; she demanded, picking up one of her shoes. I eyed the wicked heel on it and put up both my hands in supplication.<br>
<br>
&quot;Eva, put down the shoe.&quot; I could just see that heel buried in my eye.<br>
<br>
&quot;Who is she?&quot; she repeated.<br>
<br>
&quot;Alyssa Thissel.&quot; I replied, closing my eyes. Maybe she would miss.<br>
<br>
Nothing happened. I opened one eye. Eva had dropped the shoe and was staring at me with disgust.<br>
<br>
&quot;Alyssa Thissel?&quot; she asked slowly. &quot;Your dead partner's wife?&quot;<br>
<br>
I winced at the implication. &quot;Yeah, Ice's wife.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Shouldn't you have waited until he was dead at least three weeks?!&quot; Here came the shoe. But I was ready for it, and it sailed to my left.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's a long story...&quot; I tried, but she was reaching for the other shoe.<br>
<br>
Grabbing my badge and crossbow, I bolted for the door.<br>
<br>
&quot;And she's a Drow!&quot; I heard from inside the house, punctuated by the shoe bouncing off the closed door. Then another lamp.<br>
<br>
I shook my head sadly and walked home.  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 244<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/14/03 6:52:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All Rise (BloodOath Part II)</span><hr size=1> Alyssa Thissel, (Alyssa MORDRIL, I corrected myself), was now my new wife, having only been widowed three weeks since my partner was killed by a dagger to the heart. It's not as cold-blooded as it sounds; I didn't just take the opportunity to wed my deceased friend's wife. If it were up to me, I would have just gone to the funeral and given her a shoulder to cry upon. But Alyssa and Danell &quot;Ice&quot; Thissel were Drow, the black elves, and they have a custom bordering on religion called Blood Oath. Blood Oath allows a dying man to enlist another to avenge his death. Upon avenging that death, however, the man enlisted takes on all the responsibilities of the dead man, including marrying his wife and raising his children. I was the man Ice named in his dying breath. He didn't have any children (thank gods) but Alyssa was now mine to support. Not that I really mind. Alyssa was a good friend before the tragedy, and I would have helped out anyway I could, but taking TOTAL responsibility was another thing altogether. I had to let go of my bachelor pad and move into her house in order to reduce financial expenses. I sleep in the guest room, of course. Alyssa may be a beautiful woman, but she was my best friend's wife, and red-blooded or not, the thought of sleeping with her didn't cross my mind. Much. Not that I would have gotten anywhere anyway. Drow only have sexual relations to reproduce, and one addition to my household was enough for now. Plus, Alyssa would probably knock my head off if I tried anything anyhow.<br>
<br>
My salary as a detective for the Guard would just pull us by. My new partner, Filbin Rucksack, was less than an ideal replacement for Ice. Filbin was a kip, a race that looked like seven year old human children, only with beards and moustaches. And this particular kip had an attitude problem. He didn't smoke, didn't drink booze, didn't chase women, played by ALL the rules. More to the point, he didn't believe in ANY of the ideals that I held dear. And furthermore, he was allergic to DOGS.<br>
<br>
Big deal, you say. Well, it IS. It's difficult enough dealing with Mr. No Fun Rucksack. But I'm a lycanthrope, a closet werewolf that turns into a shaggy beast when my world's two moons are full at the same time. It's my well kept secret, known only by Alyssa and me, but if Filbin started having a sneezing fit every night he's out with me....well, it might not stay a secret for long.<br>
<br>
He and every other cop on the Guard are looking at me strangely now anyway. Marrying your partner's wife after only three weeks of his death isn't very prudent. Not if you can't let them know about Blood Oath. Most people in Silverdane wouldn't care about any Drow customs anyway, since they consider the Drow almost a sub-species because of the color of their skin. But on top of that, I'd have to explain that I was the one that murdered Vilgore, the man who killed Ice. As it is, they think that a wild dog ripped him apart. If I told the truth, not only would I be shunned by the town and lose my job for being a rabid werewolf, but I'd be thrown in jail for overriding the justice system and murdering a suspect in cold blood. Not that he didn't deserve it.<br>
<br>
I arrived at the end of the block and looked up at Ice's cottage (MY cottage, I corrected myself. I'm paying for it now).<br>
<br>
It was a nice home, as warm inside as the Drow could manage. They were a strange race, the Drow were. Silver hair, pointed ears, and almost expressionless silver eyes. A beautiful race once you got past the jet black skin and the prejudice that accompanied it. <br>
<br>
I went inside to greet my wife.  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 245<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/14/03 6:54:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All Rise (BloodOath Part II)</span><hr size=1> &quot;You're late for dinner. &quot; Alyssa said, taking her empty plate to the wash area. She didn't look angry. My plate sat at my spot at the table. My food would be ice cold by now, but that was the price I paid for coming home late. I would just have to get used to that. And a few other things.<br>
<br>
&quot;So,&quot; she said, washing her dish, &quot;Did you have a good time with your girlfriend?&quot; A smile played across her lips. I squirmed in my seat. Every day I recieved this question, and I still couldn't shake off the feeling that I shouldn't be seeing anyone. But Hells, we had discussed this on our uneventful wedding night. I would go out and get my sex whenever I wished, as long as I didn't leave her up all night thinking I had wolfed out somewhere. It didn't make it easier.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well,&quot; I said, &quot;I almost got killed by a shoe when I told Eva I was married.&quot;<br>
<br>
She broke into the giggles. Before I married her, I wouldn't have thought her capable of laughter. Just not a Drow thing. &quot;When are you going to stop telling the truth, Lennon?&quot;<br>
<br>
I mumbled something into my fork. She quieted the giggles and continued to clean the pots. Then she looked up, suddenly remembering.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, by the way, Relgin stopped by. He wants to see you first thing tomorrow morning when you report to work.&quot;<br>
<br>
Relgin Berringer was my captain at work, a four-foot tall white haired dwarf with a full flowing beard and moustache, and a temper like an active volcano. He rarely made housecalls, unless I was in trouble. I used to get LOTS of housecalls.<br>
<br>
&quot;What did he want?&quot; I asked, concerned. I pushed the plate away from me. I'd just have to heat it up later. <br>
<br>
&quot;He wouldn't say.&quot; she replied. She dried the last pot and put it away on a shelf. Then she turned to face me. &quot;You know, everyone's been looking at us funny since the marriage, including Relgin, but this time he wouldn't even look me in the eye. Like he was embarrassed or something. He said for you not to come by tonight, it wasn't that important that it wouldn't wait until the morning. I offered him some coffee but he said his wife would kill him if he didn't get home.&quot; <br>
<br>
That sounded like Relgin's wife, but the Captain never passed on a cup of coffee. My concerns grew.<br>
<br>
&quot;I hope everything's all right.&quot; Alyssa said, heading toward the bedroom. &quot;I'm going to sleep. See you tomorrow.&quot;<br>
<br>
I wrapped up my meal and put it in the ice chest. Relgin's behavior had me unnerved. My appetite was gone. I looked over my shoulder at the bedroom door, and then to the guestroom where I would be staying. What did Relgin want?<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm glad SOMEONE will be sleeping tonight.&quot; I muttered, and headed off to bed. <br>
<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 246<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/14/03 6:56:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All Rise (BloodOath Part II)</span><hr size=1> &quot;Where's my damn coffee?&quot; Relgin shouted from behind the mess of papers on his desk. I stood waiting patiently with my hands clasped behind my back. Relgin tossed the papers to the floor and asked again. A small, childlike head poked its way into the office. It was my partner, Filbin. His moustache and beard looked like it was drawn on.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll get it, boss.&quot; he offered. Relgin grunted and Filbin scampered off. What an ass-kisser.<br>
<br>
Relgin wouldn't look at me as we waited in uncomfortable silence for Filbin to return. He did after two fidgety minutes, and after placing the cup ceremoniously in front of Relgin, waited for us to begin. One glare from the Captain informed him he would not get to watch me being chewed out. With a sad look he silently exited the office. Regin followed him to the door and closed it as he left. Then he returned to his desk and folded his massive arms across his chest. His eyes wandered everywhere but on me. I cleared my throat.<br>
<br>
&quot;Um, chief, this meeting was your idea, remember?&quot;<br>
<br>
He looked startled, but recovered, to a degree. &quot;Ah, yeah...&quot; he said in that deep voice of his. &quot;Well, Lennon, I called you in here because...well...&quot; He finally looked at me. &quot;Well, we have a rather large problem.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, I didn't think you wanted to get together for a poker game.&quot; I replied. &quot;What's going on?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well,&quot; he said, taking a deep breath. I wondered if I was fired. &quot;Well, Zo is suing the department for you pulling that crossbow on him last month.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah.&quot; I said, not too surprised. Zo was a special informant for the Guard, a walking library of information. He was also a wizard of rather high reputation and stature in Silverdane. And, more importantly, he was a thief when it came to the ridiculous prices he charged us for his information. On my last case things had gotten a little out of hand with Zo, and I held a loaded crossbow to his head in order to get some crucial information. I expected a lawsuit the moment I did it, but I wasn't quite myself at the time. But for Relgin to beat around the bush for something like this was unusual. Zo was ALWAYS suing someone for something.<br>
<br>
&quot;What else?&quot; I asked, and waited. A full minute passed, and then Relgin got right to the point.<br>
<br>
&quot;You've been implicated in the murders of Ot-Ot Demonspawn and your partner, Ice.&quot;<br>
<br>
My jaw hit the floor. <br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 259<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/25/03 6:21:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All Rise (BloodOath Part II)</span><hr size=1> &quot;WHAT?&quot; I exclaimed, staring at him. &quot;You know what happened that night!&quot;<br>
<br>
Relgin stared at me sadly. &quot;I know what you TOLD me, Lennon.&quot; The tone set me aback<br>
.<br>
&quot;Ice and I went to the Brimstone Club to find Ot-Ot so he could testify against Vilgore as a witness to a murder. When we got there Ot-Ot was already dead with his throat cut. The same person...VILGORE...then killed Ice with the same dagger. Vilgore's dead now. End of story.&quot; I looked at him, daring him to contradict me. Which he did.<br>
<br>
&quot;Lennon,&quot; he started softly. &quot;This is all what YOU told me. You also claimed you didn't actually SEE Vilgore there.&quot; Which I didn't; I SMELLED Vilgore, but I wasn't about to tell him I was a werewolf. &quot;Also, the city has over a dozen witnesses that will claim you killed Ice and Ot-Ot walked in on it, so you killed him too.&quot; This took me for a loop. &quot;And finally,&quot; he added uncomfortably, &quot;The fact that you married your partner's wife three weeks after his death does not make you look very good.&quot;<br>
<br>
That silenced any retort on my part. I wanted to scream out that I only married her because I avenged Ice's death, but I would only succeed in admitting to ANOTHER murder. Instead I just looked at him.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm sorry, Lennon.&quot; he said when it seemed I would remain silent for the rest of the day. He got up from his desk and poked his head out the door. Two guards entered the room. With shackles. <br>
<br>
Relgin solemnly took my crossbow from me. My hands were bound behind me. Relgin's face looked sick. <br>
<br>
He reached into my pocket and withdrew my badge. I felt like I might throw up. He would not meet my eyes. And worse, I could not meet his.<br>
<br>
&quot;You have the right to remain silent.&quot; he intoned. I had said the same thing a million times before. I never thought I'd have it said to me.<br>
<br>
&quot;If you choose to give up this right, anything you may say will be held against you in the High Court.....&quot;<br>
<br>
You know the rest.  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 260<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/25/03 6:22:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All Rise (BloodOath Part II)</span><hr size=1> There is nothing more bleak than the inside of a Guardhouse prison cell. Grey stone walls, a bucket for waste, and bars. Bars I was only familiar with from the other side. Now I was on the inside, and feeling extremely sorry for myself.<br>
<br>
Fortunately Relgin had the good sense not to throw me into the holding cell with the other prisoners we kept. Most of those were habitual offenders, and I had previously arrested at least half of them. A night in lockup and I'd be ripped to pieces. The cell I was in was a special cell meant for extremely dangerous criminals, so I had it all to myself. I didn't know whether that was good or bad.<br>
<br>
