The jury nodded as one. They were picked the day before, after Galpin left me to ponder in my cell. It didn't go too badly, on the whole. Of the nine jury members, only two were hybrids. There were no elves or Drow, as Galpin had predicted. Three kippings, which wouldn't mean anything to either side. Only one dwarf, which was unfortunate. Even though I was a human, a dwarf might be more swayed by Galpin than a bunch of kippings. But the more important thing was the human count, which was three, two men and one woman. The other females on the jury were one of the hybrids, and two of the kips. Five men, four women. Now which one was the jury leader? I hoped it was one of the two human men. The jury leader, chosen by a closed vote within the jury, would be who led them through their deciding stage of the trial and read the verdict. The position, though only as important as I just described, also had a tendency to sway jury decision to whichever way he or she decided. Not a sure thing, but damned close. A human male would hopefully fix this case for me.<br>
