<br>
&quot;Next witness.&quot; the judge intoned.  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 272<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/4/03 2:29:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All Rise (BloodOath Part II)</span><hr size=1> After the job Galpin did on him, it seemed Chelton didn't want to bring out his parade of hybrid witnesses to claim they had actually seen me kill Ice and Ot-Ot. I could understand why. Whatever story the hybrids had concocted to describe how I killed them both would fall apart in light of Elrith's damning testimony.<br>
<br>
&quot;So you have no other witnesses?&quot; Allimore asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, no, your Honor.&quot; Chelton said apologetically. &quot;But I have two experts coming in from Black Haven tomorrow, my own forensics people. They should arrive tonight. I also would like to question Alyssa Mordril.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Alright.&quot; Judge Allimore decided. &quot;We'll call it a day and reconviene here tomorrow at noon.&quot; He banged down his gavel and exited the room.<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't know what he expects with these &quot;experts&quot; Galpin said to me, &quot;But we'll take care of them tomorrow. As to Alyssa's testimony, frankly I'm concerned about it. We need to talk, tonight.&quot;<br>
<br>
I gulped. &quot;Sure. Nice job up there.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;He made it easy.&quot; Galpin said, gesturing to Chelton. &quot;See you tonight.&quot; And he left.<br>
<br>
Well, that was a productive day. Captain Relgin returned me to my cell. <br>
<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 273<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/4/03 2:30:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All Rise (BloodOath Part II)</span><hr size=1> Galpin never showed at my cell that night. I was concerned, but deep down I felt a sense of relief. My marriage to Alyssa and obligation to Blood Oath was something I did not want to discuss, and I took his absense as his acknowledgement of my feeling on it. I pondered why Balkin Grogg would lie about what happened. Nevertheless, I slept soundly that night, assured the next day would find me vindicated.<br>
<br>
At court the next day, Galpin Berringer did not show.  <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 274<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/4/03 2:31:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All Rise (BloodOath Part II)</span><hr size=1> &quot;I'm afraid I will have to postpone this case for a week.&quot; Judge Allimore said, his face grave. &quot;Mr. Berringer will no longer be able to try this case. An alternate will have to be found.&quot;<br>
<br>
A murmur of surprise went through the courtroom. No one was more suprised, however, than me. Except perhaps Chelton Keller.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your Honor,&quot; he protested. &quot;If Mr. Berringer chooses to drop from this case it's his perogative. I would myself if the facts were as dead set against me as they were against him. But to delay the case a week will upset my experts' schedules and...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Mr. Keller, Mr. Berringer did not drop this case because of anything that has transpired in this courtroom.&quot; Allimore said icily. &quot;Mr. Berringer can no longer try this case because he was found stabbed to death early this morning.&quot; He smacked down his gavel. The courtroom was struck dumb.<br>
<br>
&quot;This trial will continue one week from today at noon. Till then this court is adjourned.&quot; <br>
<br>
 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 275<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/4/03 2:33:20 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All Rise (BloodOath Part II)</span><hr size=1> Stabbed to death. I had been led back to my cell in a state of numb shock. Now I knew why Relgin hadn't been the one to bring me to the courtroom. His brother was dead.<br>
<br>
Why? Why kill a lawyer? My head reeled. Was he killed because he was doing such a good job in my defense? Or was it just one of those senseless, random things? If it was because of me, who would want me in jail so badly they would kill for it?<br>
<br>
And what about Balkin Grogg? Galpin had made him look like a fool on the stand. A fellow dwarf had humiliated him. Grogg would be pissed, for sure, but would that justify murder? Grogg wasn't stupid enough to believe he wouldn't be a prime suspect. I just couldn't figured it out. My professional life supplied enough mystery without it entering into my private life.<br>
<br>
Alyssa visited me for a half hour. We sat in silence almost the entire time, just looking at each other. We knew we had been granted a temporary reprieve concerning our marriage, but at a horrible price. We shared a certain amount of guilt, both knowing how badly we had wanted some reason for Alyssa to be kept from testifying. Well, now we had it. For a week at least.<br>
<br>
After she left, I spent the next few hours pacing back and forth, trying to push from my mind the pictures of stabbed Drow and sliced-up hybrids and gutted dwarves. The more I tried to forget the more vivid they became. And worse, the more the carnage encrouched on my conscious the more the subconscious beast within me awoke. In moments of high pressure, the shift from man to wolf could happen whether our two moons were full or not. That would be all I needed. For the guards to come in and find a huge wolf in the shredded remains of my prison clothes. As it was, if the trial went on a day longer than when it restarted next week, I would change. The moons would be full. When we reentered the courtroom next week, we had better finish the trial one way or another.<br>
<br>
I lay down in darkness and tried to sleep. I was almost there when my senses picked up a familiar smell in the room, just outside my cell. A scent no human nose would detect, but a wolf's nose would. Relgin, standing there in the dark. Watching me. Without a word.<br>
<br>
After what seemed an eternity, Relgin struck a spark to a hand-held lamp. The light flared up, leaving me blinded for a moment. A click, and he had entered my cell. When my vision returned he was standing in the cell, looking very sad. Looking very old.<br>
<br>
With a single motion, he threw the lamp to the floor. I jumped back onto my cot as flaming oil spilled everywhere, the glass breaking into a thousand pieces. Relgin stood still, unaware of the flames at his feet.<br>
<br>
&quot;Guards!&quot; he cried in a loud voice. &quot;Get in here!&quot;<br>
<br>
Several officers ran into the room, confused, taking in the burning mess. One saw me and drew his crossbow. I cringed.<br>
<br>
&quot;Get this man into Isolation immediately!&quot; Relgin demanded in a tone I have never heard him use before. &quot;He just attacked me.&quot;<br>
<br>
I was pulled roughly from the cell by my old friends. No one bothered to be gentle about it. I was too surprised to protest. Another guard rushed in to stamp out the flames before they reached the cot. The last thing I saw before I was thrown into the windowless, pitch-black, empty isolation room was Relgin's face behind the guards.<br>
<br>
It was bitter look, cold, mirthless.<br>
<br>
I could swear he was smiling. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.lby3.com/eq/leopa/misc/riverdane_animatedbanner.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=riverdane>Riverdane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 276<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/4/03 2:38:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=29.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: All Rise (BloodOath Part II)</span><hr size=1> I had no idea how much time had passed after that first hour. It could have been minutes, it could have been days. No windows, no light, no sound. Only my sense of smell remained with me, and the only thing I picked up was the smell of my own sweat. <br>
<br>
The door swung open, and the light was so blinding I had the shield my eyes. I didn't have to see to know that Relgin and two other guards were standing in the doorway.<br>
<br>
&quot;Leave us alone, I tell you!&quot; Relgin snapped at one of them. &quot;I'll be alright!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But Captain...&quot; one of them tried.<br>
<br>
&quot;I was ambushed the last time.&quot; Relgin answered harshly. &quot;Do you think he could take me a second time, with me prepared?&quot;<br>
<br>
The guard wasn't about to argue that point. With a grunt, he and his companion left. Just Relgin and I stood in the room, facing each other.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sorry it took so long to get back to you.&quot; Relgin said softly. &quot;There were things I had to do.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;How long have I been in here?&quot; I asked, surprised at the sound of my voice. It croaked. I hadn't had water since I ended up in here.<br>
<br>
&quot;Eighteen hours.&quot; Relgin said, reaching for his hip flask. He handed it to me. I grabbed it warily, and brought it to my nose. Odorless. Water. I drank it slowly, controlling myself. I didn't know how much more I'd get. When I finished I looked down at him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Why?&quot; I asked simply.<br>
<br>
Relgin's face bore no apology. &quot;I had to get you in here. And I had to make it rough, or they would never have believed it.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Why?&quot; I asked again.<br>
<br>
&quot;My baby brother is dead.&quot; And finally his face bore some emotion. Not a lot. But enough.<br>
<br>
&quot;My mother came in this afternoon.&quot; he said. &quot;She was hysterical, screaming and flailing out and crying. I had to use a sleep potion to knock her out. Funny, she always thought I'd be the one to bite it first. Not Gal. Not Mr. School Galpin.&quot; His face scrunched up a bit, an alien, strange, horrifying look. Please don't cry, Relgin. I don't think I could stand to see it. A man should never see his boss cry.<br>
<br>
&quot;He was stabbed twenty-seven times. Twenty-seven! A knife prefered by hybrids. They found him in Bee-Bee Devilbreed's apartment, naked, sprawled out next to her. She was killed too, same knife, eighteen stab wounds, more than half fatal. Both of them, naked, my brother and a hybrid prostitute. Red and black blood everywhere. Word on the street is that Galpin took her up on that offer she made in court. And that one of her regulars found her in the sack with him, didn't like it, and killed them both.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Galpin wasn't having sex with Bee-Bee.&quot; I said quietly.<br>
<br>
Relgin stared at me. &quot;How do you know that? You're correct, you know. The coroner's report showed no sexual activity had happened. But they could have been killed before anything... happened.&quot; I could see from his face that the thought of his brother and a hybrid whore in a blonde wig revolted him. It revolted ME.<br>
<br>
&quot;There was no way Galpin and Bee-Bee were having sex, interrupted or not.&quot; I said with certainty.<br>
<br>
&quot;How do you know?&quot; Relgin asked again, watching me closely.<br>
<br>
&quot;They were both killed and arranged to look like they were. I knew Bee-Bee, very well. She was a talker, and those walks back to the Guardhouse after we'd bust her were long ones. She prided herself on never having to take off her clothes to service a client. Had her clothes tailored for...easy entry. Faster service, she called it. She tried to show us one night, but Ice told her our imaginations would suffice. She wouldn't have taken off her clothes to be with your brother. If she was found naked someone undressed her. Someone who didn't know Bee-Bee. Someone from out of town.&quot;<br>
<br>
Relgin smiled and tossed me a cigarette. He pulled out a cigar and lit it, then lit mine. I inhaled deeply. I had forgotten how badly I needed one.<br>
<br>
&quot;You're right, you know. It WAS someone out of town.&quot;<br>
<br>
I exhaled and waited for him to explain.<br>
<br>
&quot;I went to Zo.&quot; he said. &quot;I know, I know. Magic is inadmissable in court, and magic identity traces are wrong half of the time. But I didn't care. I did it on my own time, and with my own money. It cost me a month's salary.&quot; I snorted. I knew Zo's prices. Relgin blew out his smoke, eyes vacant as he continued.<br>
<br>
&quot;Zo wasn't certain, but he sent me in the direction of Eddie's Greasy Spoon. I found the guy in a room upstairs. New in town, two days paid in advance, from Trillmore. Wanted to know if I had a warrant. Cocky. Arrogant.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What did you do?&quot; I asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;I knocked out his teeth. Told him that was my warrant. And as he lay writhing on the floor, I searched his room. And found a knife, hybrid-make, in one of his dresser drawers.&quot;<br>
<br>
I stared at him.<br>
<br>
&quot;It took two hours for me to beat the information out of him. But I got it. He was sent from Trillmore to kill my brother when it looked like he'd get you aquitted. Someone in the courthouse had seen the number my brother had done on Chelton and wanted to make sure you stayed in jail. Whoever it was contacted this guy, who was waiting to see which way it would go. Then he left for Trillmore after telling the assassin to kill Galpin and make it look like a jealous customer of Bee-Bee's.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Trillmore?&quot; I asked. &quot;Dark Rotunda?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes.&quot; Relgin said. &quot;Rotunda wants you in jail. Now I know where all the pressure was coming from to have you tried quickly. Rotunda could blackmail half of the politicians in Silverdane. He had my brother killed to keep you locked up. Why?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The crystal.&quot; I whispered, resigned. &quot;He wanted the crystal.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The diamond crystal is in Black Haven.&quot; Relgin pointed out.<br>
<br>
&quot;Not the diamond crystal.&quot; I said quietly. &quot;The glass crystal.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The glass crystal.&quot; Relgin repeated. &quot;The crystal Vilgore had.&quot;<br>
<br>
I nodded.<br>
<br>
&quot;You killed him.&quot; It was a statement, not a question. &quot;I had thought you had, but couldn't figure out how....&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;And the assassin after he confessed?&quot; I asked softly.<br>
<br>
Relgin puffed furiously on his cigar. &quot;Let's just say I understand vengence just as well as you do.&quot;<br>
<br>
Smoke hung between us. That and an unspoken bond. We both had our secrets from the rest of the world.<br>
<br>
&quot;Another thing.&quot; Relgin said, breaking the silence. &quot;Your box of personal items was stolen from Inventory. Rotunda must have had it stolen for the crystal. The spy from the courtroom probably has it halfway to Trillmore by now.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;The crystal isn't in it.&quot; I said. &quot;Alyssa has it.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'll post a guard on the house to watch her.&quot; Relgin promised. &quot;I understand why you killed Vilgore. I liked Ice too. But why did you have to marry his wife?&quot;<br>
<br>
I inhaled deeply. &quot;Blood Oath. Drow custom. A LONG story.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Good.&quot; he told me, not pressing it further. &quot;You can tell me when you get back.&quot;<br>
<br>
That took me for a loop. &quot;Get back?&quot; I asked. &quot;From where?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Why do you think I had to get you into Isolation?&quot; he asked me. &quot;I told everyone that I would be the only one to see you, to knock some sense into your head. You're going to Trillmore to get a confession from Rotunda. You have six more days before your trial starts again. There's a way out of this area, a secret that gets passed from captain to captain. No one else knows about it. No one will even know you're gone.&quot; He swung the door open for me, looked to make sure no guards were loitering around, and gestured me out. He pushed a small bag of silver into one of my hands. Into the other he placed a hybrid-made knife.<br>
<br>
&quot;Be invisible.&quot; he said. I nodded and stepped out of the cell.<br>
<br>
I was free. <br>
